\section{\texorpdfstring{\textbf{Phase 1 - Introduction, Cleaning, and
Exploration}}{Phase 1 - Introduction, Cleaning, and Exploration}}\label{phase-1---introduction-cleaning-and-exploration}

\subsection{Outline}\label{outline}

The prescribed data set contained advertising metrics provided by a
prominent search engine. The data contained several descriptive features
pertaining to a range of information. Finally, the target feature was a
measure of revenue associated with each of the observations.\\
The dataset was used to create a supervised machine learning model to
predict values for the target feature. Phase 1 of this report contains
the introduction, cleaning, and exploration of the dataset. Phase 2
contains the creation, training, and deployment of the machine learning
algorithm.

\subsubsection{Nature of the Data}\label{nature-of-the-data}

The below is an exerpt from accompanying documentation about the
dataset.

Features in this data set are as follows:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  companyId: Company ID of record (categorical)
\item
  countryId: Country ID of record (categorical)
\item
  deviceType: Device type of record (categorical corresponding to
  desktop, mobile, tablet)
\item
  day: Day of record (integer between 1 (oldest) and 30 for train, 31
  and 35 (most recent) for test)
\item
  dow: Day of week of the record (categorical)
\item
  price1, price2, price3: Price combination for the record set by the
  company (numeric)
\item
  ad\_area: area of advertisement (numeric)
\item
  ad\_ratio: ratio of advertisement's length to its width (numeric)
\item
  requests, impression, cpc, ctr, viewability: Various metrics related
  to the record (numeric)
\item
  ratio1, \ldots{}, ratio5: Ratio characteristics related to the record
  (numeric)
\item
  y (target feature): revenue-related metric (numeric)
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Target Feature}\label{target-feature}

The column/variable \textbf{y} was selected as the target feature in the
dataset.

\paragraph{Descriptive Features}\label{descriptive-features}

All other columns/variables in the dataset, as outlined above, were
chosen as descriptive features.

\subsubsection{Classifying Data}\label{classifying-data}

R and \texttt{dplyr} parse data files to guessed data types when loaded.
Typically, columns with text are parsed as \texttt{character} type,
columns with digits are parsed as \texttt{numeric}, and boolean columns
are parsed as \texttt{logical}. Per the above feature definitions, the
categorical data was re-classified as \texttt{factor}s.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{advertising_train}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{companyId <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{as.factor}\NormalTok{(advertising_train}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{companyId)}

\NormalTok{advertising_train}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{countryId <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{as.factor}\NormalTok{(advertising_train}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{countryId)}

\NormalTok{advertising_train}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{deviceType <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{as.factor}\NormalTok{(advertising_train}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{deviceType)}

\NormalTok{advertising_train}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{dow <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{as.factor}\NormalTok{(advertising_train}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{dow)}

\KeywordTok{sapply}\NormalTok{(advertising_train, class)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\paragraph{Categorical and Non-Numeric
Features}\label{categorical-and-non-numeric-features}

When examining the frequencies of individual levels of each Categorical
(non-numeric) descriptive feature, variability was observed in
\texttt{companyId}, \texttt{countryId}, and \texttt{deviceType}. Far
less variability in frequencies was observed in \texttt{dow}, with
Sunday being the only day of the week to return a markedly lower
frequency.

\paragraph{Logarithmic
Transformations}\label{logarithmic-transformations}

It was observed from the plots above that natural logarithmic
transformations were applicable for descriptive features \texttt{cpc},
\texttt{impression}, and potentially \texttt{ctr}. Target feature
\texttt{y} was also suitable for a logarithmic transformation.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{advertising_train <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(advertising_train,}
                            \StringTok{"ln_cpc"}\NormalTok{ =}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{log}\NormalTok{(cpc }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }\FloatTok{0.005}\NormalTok{),}
                            \StringTok{"ln_ctr"}\NormalTok{ =}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{log}\NormalTok{(ctr }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }\FloatTok{0.005}\NormalTok{),}
                            \StringTok{"ln_impr"}\NormalTok{ =}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{log}\NormalTok{(impression }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }\FloatTok{0.005}\NormalTok{),}
                            \StringTok{"ln_req"}\NormalTok{ =}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{log}\NormalTok{(requests }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }\FloatTok{0.005}\NormalTok{),}
                            \StringTok{"ln_y"}\NormalTok{ =}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{log}\NormalTok{(y }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }\FloatTok{0.005}\NormalTok{))}

\NormalTok{sample_adv <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{sample_n}\NormalTok{(advertising_train, }\DecValTok{20}\NormalTok{)}

\KeywordTok{kable_styling}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{kable}\NormalTok{(sample_adv[ , }\DecValTok{1} \OperatorTok{:}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{floor}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{ncol}\NormalTok{(sample_adv)}\OperatorTok{/}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{) ],}

              \DataTypeTok{font_size =} \FloatTok{8.5}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{latex_options =} \KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"striped"}\NormalTok{),}

\KeywordTok{kable_styling}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{kable}\NormalTok{(sample_adv[ , }\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\KeywordTok{seq}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{from =} \KeywordTok{floor}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{ncol}\NormalTok{(sample_adv)}\OperatorTok{/}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}\OperatorTok{+}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}

\paragraph{Comparison of Transformed Features to Normal
Curve}\label{comparison-of-transformed-features-to-normal-curve}

As the logarithmic transformation resulted in infinite values, the data
frame was trimmed to only include finite values. The finite data frame
was then used to calculate the centre and spread of \texttt{ln\_cpc},
\texttt{ln\_ctr}, \texttt{ln\_impr}, \texttt{ln\_req}, and
\texttt{ln\_y}.

The natural logarithmic transformations of \texttt{impression} and
\texttt{requests} clearly approached a normal distribution. The
transformed \texttt{y} target feature somewhat resembled a normal
distribution, albeit less closely as compared to \texttt{impression}.
Both \texttt{cpc} and \texttt{ctr} appeared to be bimodal distributions
after logarithmic transformation, with \texttt{ln\_ctr} inarguably so.

\subsubsection{Multivariate Plots}\label{multivariate-plots}

After transformation, grouping the \texttt{ln\_ctr} distribution by
level within the \texttt{companyId} factor revealed several distinct
distributions. The distribution for \texttt{companyId} == 43 still
appeared bimodal, which possibly indicated a further dimension of the
multivariate relationship.

The remaining numeric features (\texttt{ad\_area}, \texttt{ad\_ratio},
\texttt{day}, \texttt{ratio1}, \texttt{ratio2}, \texttt{ratio3},
\texttt{ratio4}, \texttt{ratio5}, and \texttt{viewability}) were not
able to be transformed to distributions that approached normal curves
via root or logarithmic methods. Despite the accompanying documentation
for the prescribed dataset, the \texttt{ad\_area} and \texttt{day} may
not strictly be classed as numeric/double variables. Considering the low
range, \texttt{ad\_area} could be intepreted as an identifier, and so
categorical. The feature \texttt{day}, values 1 - 30, is better
interpreted as an ordinal or time value. However, time series
forecasting is outside the scope of this project, and so the
\texttt{day} feature will be largely ignored from the model and only
used for partitioning.

\paragraph{Data Normalisation}\label{data-normalisation}

Considering each of the features span differing ranges, both in their
raw and transformed applications, it was deemed necessary to normalise
each. Normalising the data allowed for more

As outlined in \textbf{Fundamentals of Machine Learning}, the below
formula was used for normalising the data:

\[ a^{'}_{i} = \left( \frac{a_i-min(a)}{max(a)-min(a)} \right) \times (high - low) + low \]

Where \(a\) is the feature, whether descriptive or target, \(high\) is
the highest value in the normalised data range, and \(low\) is the
lowest value in the normalised data range. A range of 0 - 1 was chosen,
so these values were used for \(low\) and \(high\) respectively.

\NormalTok{  x[}\KeywordTok{is.infinite}\NormalTok{(x)] <-}\StringTok{ }\OtherTok{NA}
  
\NormalTok{  (((x }\OperatorTok{-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{min}\NormalTok{(x, }\DataTypeTok{na.rm =}\NormalTok{ T)) }\OperatorTok{/}
\StringTok{      }\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{max}\NormalTok{(x, }\DataTypeTok{na.rm =}\NormalTok{ T) }\OperatorTok{-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{min}\NormalTok{(x, }\DataTypeTok{na.rm =}\NormalTok{ T))) }\OperatorTok{*}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1} \OperatorTok{-}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{)}
  
\NormalTok{\}}

\subsubsection{Discretising Target
Feature}\label{discretising-target-feature}

Random Forests, Decision Trees, and K-Nearest Neighbours methods of
machine learning function best when predicting categorical variables. As
such, the transformed target feature,
\texttt{norm\textbackslash{}\_ln\textbackslash{}\_y} was classified into
six equal-width bins; 1 to 6.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{advertising_train <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(advertising_train,}
                            \StringTok{"norm_ln_y_binned"}\NormalTok{ =}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{as.factor}\NormalTok{((norm_ln_y }\OperatorTok{%/%}\StringTok{ }\FloatTok{0.2}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{))}

\KeywordTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(advertising_train) }\OperatorTok{+}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{geom_bar}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ norm_ln_y_binned),}
           \DataTypeTok{stat =} \StringTok{"count"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{bins =} \DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{,}
           \DataTypeTok{fill =} \StringTok{"cyan3"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{alpha =} \DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{/}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{+}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{stat_count}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ norm_ln_y_binned,}

\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{scale_y_continuous}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{labels =}\NormalTok{ comma,}

\subsubsection{Subsetting Data Frame}\label{subsetting-data-frame}

Due to constraints on computing power, it was deemed necessary to subset
the data frame to a smaller number of rows.

\begin{Shaded}

                                     \DataTypeTok{size =} \DecValTok{1998}\NormalTok{,}
                                     \DataTypeTok{replace =}\NormalTok{ F)}

\NormalTok{advertising_train_subset <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{rbind}\NormalTok{(advertising_train_subset,}

\NormalTok{                                         norm_ln_y }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{max}\NormalTok{(norm_ln_y) }\OperatorTok{|}
\StringTok{                                           }\NormalTok{norm_ln_y }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{min}\NormalTok{(norm_ln_y)))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

greater than typical values that can be handled by machine learning
algorithms, so was futher discretised to 26 bins; 1:26.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]

\KeywordTok{sort}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{unique}\NormalTok{(advertising_train}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{countryId_bin))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\NormalTok{advertising_train_subset <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{rbind}\NormalTok{(advertising_train_subset,}

\NormalTok{                                         norm_ln_y }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{max}\NormalTok{(advertising_train}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{norm_ln_y,}

\StringTok{                                           }\NormalTok{norm_ln_y }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{min}\NormalTok{(advertising_train}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{norm_ln_y,}
                                                            \DataTypeTok{na.rm =}\NormalTok{ T)))}

\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ (i }\ControlFlowTok{in} \KeywordTok{levels}\NormalTok{(advertising_train}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{countryId_bin)) \{}
  
\NormalTok{  temp <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{filter}\NormalTok{(advertising_train,}
\NormalTok{                 countryId_bin }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{i)}
  
\NormalTok{  advertising_train_subset <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{rbind}\NormalTok{(advertising_train_subset,}

\NormalTok{\}}

\subsubsection{K-Nearest Neighbours on Transformed
Data}\label{k-nearest-neighbours-on-transformed-data}

The K-Nearest Neighbours performed above was prior to futher data
preparation. As such, KNN was repeated using the most recently
transformed data frame.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{fused_Model_kknn2 <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{mlr}\OperatorTok{::}\KeywordTok{train}\NormalTok{(fusedLrn_kknn,}
\NormalTok{                           classif_task)}

\NormalTok{prediction_fused_kknn2 <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{predict}\NormalTok{(fused_Model_kknn,}
                                  \DataTypeTok{newdata =}\NormalTok{ advertising_train)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
